\begin_layout Section
Momentum formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conservative formulation uses the momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $(hu,hv)$
\end_inset

 as the conserved quantities.
 In this form, the equations are given as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{t}+(hu)_{x}+(hv)_{y}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(hu)_{t}+(hu^{2}+\frac{1}{2}gh^{2})_{x}+(huv)_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(hv)_{t}+(hv^{2}+\frac{1}{2}gh^{2})_{y}+(huv)_{x}+fu=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since this formulation is conserving the momentum, it is also refered as
 the conservative form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Please note, that this formulation contains several non-linear terms!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Non-conservative formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By using the produce rule, we can reformulate the equations above to make
 the velocities conserved quantities.
 Here, we first apply the produce rule to 
\begin_inset Formula $(hu)_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
hu_{t}+h_{t}u+h_{x}u^{2}+2huu_{x}+ghh_{x}+(hu)_{y}v+huv_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
hu_{t}+(-(hu)_{x}-(hv)_{y})u+h_{x}u^{2}+2huu_{x}+ghh_{x}+(hv)_{y}u+hvu_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
hu_{t}+(-(hu)_{x})u+h_{x}u^{2}+2huu_{x}+ghh_{x}+hvu_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
hu_{t}-h_{x}uu-huu{}_{x}+h_{x}u^{2}+2huu_{x}+ghh_{x}+hvu_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}+gh_{x}+uu_{x}+vu_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alltogether, we get the following non-conservative formulation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{t}+(hu)_{x}+(hv)_{y}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}+gh_{x}+uu_{x}+vu_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}+gh_{y}+uv_{x}+vv_{y}+fu=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Vorticity formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For certain reasons such as energy and enstropy conservation, the equations
 are reformulated and split into the vorticity and H component.
 We first add an artificial term 
\begin_inset Formula $vv_{x}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}-vv_{x}+gh_{x}+uu_{x}+vv_{x}+vu_{y}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}-vv_{x}+vu_{y}+(gh+u^{2}+v^{2})_{x}-fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and set 
\begin_inset Formula $H:=gh+u^{2}+v^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta:=v_{x}-u_{y}+f$
\end_inset

, yielding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}-v\eta+H_{x}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, we can reformulate 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}+gh_{y}+uv_{x}+vv_{y}+uu_{y}-uu_{y}+fu=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}+uv_{x}-uu_{y}+fu+(gh+v^{2}+u^{2})=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This yields the vorticity formulation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{t}+(hu)_{x}+(hv)_{y}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}-v\eta+H_{x}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}+u\eta+H_{y}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Full linearization with perturbation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations can be linearized around a perturbation 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p_{0}+p'$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\{h,u,v\}$
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

denoting a constant steady state.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $a'b'<O(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

, we can use
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(ab)_{x}=((a_{0}+a')(b_{0}+b'))_{z}=(a'b_{0})_{z}+(b'a_{0})_{z}+(a'b')_{z}\approx(a'b_{0})_{z}+(b'a_{0})_{z}=b_{0}a'_{z}+a_{0}b'_{z}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to simplify the non-conservative formulation to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h'_{t}+h_{0}(u'_{x}+v'_{x})+h'_{x}(u_{0}+v_{0})=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, we assume a low velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|u_{0}|,|v_{0}|\}<O(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

, yielding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h'_{t}+h_{0}u'_{x}+h_{0}v'_{x}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $ab_{z}=(a_{0}+a')(b_{0}+b')_{z}=a_{0}b'_{z}+a'b'_{z}\approx a_{0}b'_{z}$
\end_inset

 , we can then simplify the non-conservative formulation to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'_{t}+gh'_{x}+u_{0}u'_{x}+v_{0}u'_{y}-fv'=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'_{t}+gh'_{y}+u_{0}v'_{x}+v_{0}v'_{y}+fu'=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and again by assuming a low velocity, get the following formulation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h'_{t}+h_{0}u'_{x}+h_{0}v'_{x}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'_{t}+gh'_{x}-fv'=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'_{t}+gh'_{y}+fu'=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $U:=(h',u',v')$
\end_inset

, we can write these equations as a linear operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(U):=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
 & h_{0}\delta_{x} & h_{0}\delta_{y}\\
g\delta_{x} &  & -f\\
g\delta_{y} & f
\end{array}\right)U
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{t}+L(U)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear/Non-linear version:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the equation above, we neglected also the non-linear velocities.
 Assuming, that their influence is of high importance, we can write the
 equations in a form which is not neglecting these equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{t}+L(U)+N(U)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N(U):=\left(\begin{array}{c}
(hu)_{x}-h_{0}u_{x}+(hv)_{y}-h_{0}v_{y}\\
uu_{x}+vu_{y}\\
uv_{x}+vv_{y}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or with the assumption of negligible perturbations of the water height,
 we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N(U):=\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
uu_{x}+vu_{y}\\
uv_{x}+vv_{y}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
